YOU are phase 3 (TESTS) of synt-multistage.

MANDATORY OUTPUT: a single JSON object. NO prose, NO markdown fences, NO comments. The response MUST start with `{` and end with `}`. Nothing at all before the first `{`, nothing at all after the last `}`.

Previous decisions (constraints, DO NOT discuss):
  name: {{ name }}
  args required: {{ args_required }}
  args properties: {{ args_properties_summary }}
  capabilities: {{ capabilities }}
  revertible: {{ revertible }}, reverse_pattern: {{ reverse_pattern }}

User request: {{ user_request }}

STRICT RULES: produce 4-6 birth tests. Each test:
  - "name": unique snake_case string.
  - "input": dict with concrete args (real values, no placeholder).
  - "expect": dict with keys from {ok, ok_count_eq, fail_count_eq, error_contains}.
  - "setup": shell string (empty if not needed).
  - "teardown": shell string (empty if not needed).

MANDATORY CASES (at least these 4):
  1. basic happy case (1 element, ok=true).
  2. empty list if the main arg is a list (ok=true, ok_count_eq=0).
  3. invalid args (ok=false, error_contains="...").
  4. domain-specific edge case (non-existent path/url, scope violation, etc.).

OUTPUT EXAMPLE (for name=delete_files):
{
  "tests": [
    {
      "name": "delete_single_file",
      "setup": "mkdir -p /tmp/t && echo x > /tmp/t/a.txt",
      "input": {"paths": ["/tmp/t/a.txt"]},
      "expect": {"ok": true, "ok_count_eq": 1},
      "teardown": "rm -rf /tmp/t"
    },
    {
      "name": "empty_list_ok",
      "setup": "",
      "input": {"paths": []},
      "expect": {"ok": true, "ok_count_eq": 0},
      "teardown": ""
    },
    {
      "name": "path_not_a_list_fails",
      "setup": "",
      "input": {"paths": "/tmp/x"},
      "expect": {"ok": false, "error_contains": "must be a list"},
      "teardown": ""
    },
    {
      "name": "non_existent_path_fails_only_that_one",
      "setup": "",
      "input": {"paths": ["/tmp/non_existent_xyz"]},
      "expect": {"ok": false, "fail_count_eq": 1, "error_contains": "does not exist"},
      "teardown": ""
    }
  ]
}

